content: Tony has recently started exploring AI technologies with a focus on practical applications. One of his current initiatives is building a portfolio-integrated AI chatbot that helps users understand his background and professional history. In parallel, he is learning the LangChain framework to build custom AI agents with Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) and document querying capabilities.

At Eszterházy Károly Catholic University, Tony leads two AI-driven projects. The first is a university-wide chatbot designed for all 1,100 employees, providing API-based access to institutional regulations and large document corpora through natural language queries. The second project focuses on educational platforms, where Tony is implementing AI-based adaptive learning pathways to personalize the learning experience for students based on their performance and progress.

Tony is deeply passionate about emerging IT technologies. While working full-time, he dedicated over a year to studying and practicing Amazon Web Services (AWS). He completed Adrian Cantrill's comprehensive AWS course (approx. 80 hours of video training) and gained hands-on experience with the most critical AWS modules. His personal portfolio site was built on an AWS infrastructure using S3, Lambda, API Gateway, SNS, and IAM roles. He successfully passed both the 'AWS Services' and 'AWS Lambda'

and gained hands-on experience with the most critical AWS modules. His personal portfolio site was built on an AWS infrastructure using S3, Lambda, API Gateway, SNS, and IAM roles. He successfully passed both the 'AWS Services' and 'AWS Lambda' challenges on Turing.com, demonstrating his strong grasp of cloud architecture and serverless solutions.

In recent years, Tony has also focused extensively on blockchain technologies. He taught himself Solidity and implemented a number of smart contracts, including a crypto micropayment system for Imagella.com using a custom token (IMGL) and fallback support for low-cost chains like Polygon, Fantom, and xDai. This system includes wallet validation, secure token transfers, and gas-optimized smart contract interactions.

His portfolio also features additional Web3 and smart contract projects, including a Sepolia testnet faucet application with cooldown and CAPTCHA verification, and a real-time Gas Fee Tracker built with Chainlink price oracles and a statically exported Next.js frontend. Tony has used tools and libraries such as Hardhat, Ethers.js, Chainlink VRF, wagmi, and RainbowKit, and has deployed projects on Sepolia, Ethereum, Polygon, and Arbitrum networks.

These experiences have provided Tony with practical skills in decentralized application development, wallet integrations, oracles, and gas optimization strategies. He continues to expand his knowledge of Web3 infrastructure and smart contract ecosystems.

His expertise includes ERC-20 and ERC-721 NFT token development, as well as writing and deploying upgradeable smart contracts using the proxy pattern.

He regularly works with Hardhat for development and testing, including modules such as hardhat-coverage and gas-reporter for measuring test coverage and gas efficiency. Projects are hosted on GitHub and use GitHub Actions for CI/CD automation in deployment workflows.

His portfolio also includes a Sepolia faucet dApp with cooldown and CAPTCHA, a real-time Gas Fee Tracker using Chainlink price oracles, and integrations with tools like Ethers.js, wagmi, RainbowKit, and Chainlink VRF. Tony has deployed projects across multiple EVM-compatible networks, including Sepolia, Ethereum, Polygon, and Arbitrum.

Tony is always open to meaningful collaboration opportunities in the fields of software engineering, blockchain development, cloud architecture, and AI applications. He enjoys working with innovative teams, contributing to technically challenging projects, and creating solutions that have real-world impact.

With extensive experience across academic, commercial, and international domains, Tony brings a strategic mindset, a deep technical foundation, and a practical approach to project delivery. He welcomes discussions around freelance consulting, remote development partnerships, or knowledge-sharing initiatives.

For professional inquiries or collaboration ideas, feel free to connect through his portfolio site or GitHub profile. He’s always interested in new ways to apply technology to solve meaningful problems.

Tony has over 26 years of experience working with relational databases, having started his software engineering career in 1999. His thesis project at the college focused on 'Automated Database Schema Design', for which he developed a fully functioning schema design application.

Throughout his career, Tony has participated in the design, normalization, and maintenance of hundreds of databases. He has used SQL extensively for decades and continues to use it intensively in modern development environments.

One of his earliest major projects was a leasing software application developed using Microsoft Visual Studio and MS SQL Server. He also spent two years in Budapest working on a risk management system related to securities investment, developed using Delphi and Oracle, with TOAD as a supporting tool for database interaction.

Beginning in 2002, Tony co-founded a software development company with his brother, a highly skilled developer. Together, they delivered numerous software projects for U.S.-based clients, where Tony often acted not only as a programmer but also as a project manager and system designer.

By 2004, Tony launched a successful online store in the U.S. focused on selling custom signage and advertising materials. He implemented highly effective English-language SEO strategies, leading the site to rank in top positions for many related keywords on Google and other search engines. The success of this platform led to the hiring of dedicated customer service staff. Tony also achieved excellent search engine visibility on Hungarian websites, frequently reaching the top 5 results for

Tony typically follows Agile software development methodologies, with a strong preference for the Kanban model in both academic and business environments. While Agile can sometimes be less efficient from a developer's perspective due to constant iteration and change, Tony recognizes that it usually results in higher user satisfaction and better long-term outcomes.

At Eszterházy Károly Catholic University, he and his team use a dedicated KanBoard system to model Kanban workflows, track progress, and document development tasks. This system provides a visual and collaborative approach to managing multi-person projects and helps ensure transparency and accountability.

In addition to KanBoard, the university relies on Microsoft SharePoint 365 for shared documentation and team collaboration. For personal and internal company projects, Tony uses SyncThing to store, synchronize, and share documents securely and efficiently without relying on cloud services.

Tony began his education in Maklár, Hungary, where he was one of the top students in mathematics and developed a strong passion for the subject. He continued his secondary education in Eger at GMSZ Technical School, specializing in manufacturing technology and computer science, earning a technical certificate.

During high school, Tony's favorite subjects were computer science and English. He obtained an intermediate-level English language certificate during his college years, but most of his real-world fluency came from business interactions and a close daily relationship with a native U.S. English-speaking professor, with whom he still speaks regularly.

Tony earned his degree with distinction from Gábor Dénes College in Eger in 2000. On the day of his final exam, he delivered the best performance among all candidates, earning an academic award during the graduation ceremony—a moment he remains proud of.

Since then, he has continued his academic journey at Eszterházy Károly University, where over the past eight years he has contributed to nearly 100 projects. His exposure to a wide array of technologies and collaboration with top experts allowed him to gain both practical and theoretical knowledge. Tony Nagy is a senior-level software engineer, technical architect, and entrepreneur with over 25 years of industry experience. He is the co-founder of Imagella LLC, a digital content platform offering millions of graphics and images, and the Head of the IT Development Division at Eszterházy Károly Catholic University in Hungary.

Tony’s expertise spans a wide range of technologies including AWS cloud architecture, Solidity smart contract development, TypeScript and React-based front-end systems, and SQL-driven backend design. He is particularly skilled at designing scalable system architectures, developing robust CI/CD pipelines, and managing full-stack projects from concept to deployment.

In addition to his hands-on technical skills, Tony has extensive experience in business development, SEO strategy, and international e-commerce. He has led multi-disciplinary teams of developers, designers, and support staff, and managed international logistics and vendor networks with over 200 suppliers.

Tony is passionate about continuous learning. He has built portfolio projects using Hardhat, OpenZeppelin libraries, Chainlink oracles, and LangChain for AI applications. His work blends innovative blockchain technology with practical cloud-based infrastructures and AI-enabled automation. As a leader, Tony is known for his system-level thinking, ability to bridge technical and business goals, and for nurturing collaborative team environments.

He is fluent in English and Hungarian and has successfully worked with clients and partners across the U.S. and Europe. His long-standing focus on software quality, strategic planning, and adaptive technology adoption makes him a uniquely valuable asset for forward-thinking organizations.

Tony has served as the technical project lead and backend developer for the National Public Education Portal (Nemzeti Köznevelési Portál – https://www.nkp.hu), operated by the Hungarian Educational Authority. The platform is a central hub for digital textbooks and smart learning materials used in Hungarian primary and secondary education. During the COVID-19 pandemic, the portal served up to 180,000 daily visitors.

Tony was responsible for designing and implementing the Elasticsearch-powered search engine as well as the backend services using Java and Maven. He coordinated a team of 16 developers and oversaw software architecture, system integration, and performance optimization.

His broader leadership role includes project coordination, stakeholder communication, requirement specifications, expert consultations, and IT planning for major EU-funded educational initiatives at Eszterházy Károly Catholic University.

Tony believes in building technology that empowers users and solves real-world challenges. He emphasizes clean code, scalability, and user-centric design in all his projects. His approach combines rigorous technical expertise with a collaborative mindset, ensuring that solutions are both innovative and practical. Tony is dedicated to mentoring junior developers and fostering a culture of continuous learning within his teams.

Tony co-founded and led Shopzeus Europe Ltd, an international e-commerce business based in Hungary, from 2008 to 2017. As CEO and technical lead, he managed a staff of 30–40 employees across departments including software development, customer service, data entry, and warehouse logistics.

He oversaw the development of in-house ERP systems, product databases, and administrative tools using Java, Delphi, PostgreSQL, and Oracle. He was responsible for system planning, architecture, and full-stack development.

Shopzeus sold products internationally on multiple platforms in the United States, United Kingdom, France, Germany, Spain, Italy, and Canada. Tony coordinated all aspects of product listing, platform integration, and digital operations with a strong emphasis on automation and scalability.

Around 2006, Tony began scaling Shopzeus's online sales operations significantly in the United States, which led to hiring additional staff and expanding logistics infrastructure. The company opened warehouses in both Florida and Hungary, managing inventory and product distribution across North America and Europe.

Shopzeus sold a diverse range of products—some were manufactured in-house, others were sourced from wholesalers, and many were imported from China to both the U.S. and EU. As the brand grew, Tony focused on business development and executive management, handling strategic negotiations in English and maintaining a dedicated U.S. phone number to directly manage partner relationships.

He gained substantial experience in executive leadership, overseeing departments including IT, logistics, accounting, and a large customer service team. Multiple companies were incorporated in different countries under the Shopzeus brand to support international operations.

At its peak in 2010, the company handled up to 500 unique orders per day, managing a catalog of tens of thousands of products from over 200 suppliers. This multinational e-commerce venture continued operating in Europe until 2017.

Tony utilizes a diverse set of development tools, frameworks, and environments across his projects. For relational database work, he primarily uses PostgreSQL, which is also the standard at Eszterházy Károly University. For AWS-based projects and fast, scalable web applications, he frequently uses DynamoDB, including on his personal portfolio site.

His preferred editor for writing code and scripts is Visual Studio Code, which he has used for many years. For Java + Elasticsearch development, he has worked extensively with the Maven build system and the Eclipse IDE.

For web development and cross-browser testing, he primarily uses Firefox and Chrome, while also validating functionality on Safari, Edge, and other browsers in institutional projects.

His blockchain development stack includes Solidity, Hardhat, TypeScript, Node.js, React, and Next.js. He configures custom RPC endpoints using Alchemy for interacting with blockchain networks. For CI/CD pipelines, he uses GitHub Actions, and for content delivery in AWS-hosted applications, such as his portfolio site, he utilizes CloudFront.

Tony actively incorporates testing and quality assurance practices into both his academic and professional work. At Eszterházy Károly Catholic University, he oversees an automated testing initiative that primarily uses Selenium for browser-based UI testing and scheduled test execution. While he does not implement the tests directly, he is fully familiar with the theoretical foundations and manages the architecture and integration aspects of the project.

In his own Solidity and blockchain development projects, Tony uses the Chai assertion library for test writing within the Hardhat framework. One of his public open-source Solidity libraries on GitHub includes automated tests and a visible coverage report, which is displayed on the repository page: https://github.com/tonynagyeurope/solidity-library

In addition to functional testing, Tony applies Prettier for automatic code formatting across several projects to maintain code consistency and readability. He also integrates GitHub Actions for CI workflows, enabling automated test execution and validation in pull request pipelines.

Since 2017, Tony has worked at Eszterházy Károly University in Eger, Hungary. Initially, he served as Deputy Director at the Institute of IT Development, which later merged with the IT Operations Department in 2022 to form a single IT Development Division. Since then, Tony has been the Head of the IT Development Division, currently managing a team of 18 employees, including software developers, data entry operators, testers, graphic designers, and customer service staff.

In this role, Tony has led the development and implementation of several educational web platforms and institutional portals, gaining extensive experience with TypeScript, React, Java, REST APIs, and Elasticsearch. He has contributed hands-on as a software developer in multiple EU-funded projects, especially Erasmus+ digital education platforms.

One of the major long-term projects under his leadership is the Nemzeti Köznevelési Portál (https://www.nkp.hu), the Hungarian National Public Education Portal. This platform delivers smart textbooks and interactive digital content to students across the country. At its peak during the COVID-19 pandemic, it served up to 180,000 users daily. Tony has over a decade of business experience in the United States, having traveled there nearly 20 times for trade shows, supplier negotiations, and strategic business meetings. At the peak of his international e-commerce operations, he maintained active business relationships with approximately 200 U.S.-based supplier companies.

His involvement included vendor management, product sourcing, logistics coordination, and long-term planning tailored to the American market. Tony built lasting partnerships and developed a deep understanding of U.S. customer expectations, business culture, and e-commerce dynamics.

He remains in regular contact with former U.S. business partners and maintains several of those relationships as lasting friendships to this day.
